 of instructive successes and failures. Among the topics Marks addresses are the scientific revolution, science as thought and performance, creationism, scientific fraud, and modern scientific racism. Applying his considerable insight, energy, and wit, Marks sheds new light on the evolution of science, its role in modern culture, and its challenges for the twenty-first century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aAnthropologyxPhilosophy. 0aEvolution (Biology)xPhilosophy. 0aSciencexPhilosophy. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Physical.2bisacsh  a21st century anthropology.  aanthropology.  aauthority.  aauto ethnography.  abiological anthropology.  acommon sense.  acreationism.  acultural power.  adisarming humor.  aevolution of science.  afield of science.  ahistory.  ainnovative.  alife sciences.  amodern culture.  amodern knowledge.  amodern scientific racism.  aphilosophy.  aphysical anthropology.  aracism.  ascience as performance.  ascience as thought.  ascience studies.  ascientific fraud.  ascientific revolution.  ascientists.  asociology.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052025959140uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052094330840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520943308423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520943308/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY